{"title_page": "Paradise Lost (band)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Paradise Lost\n| image               = Metalmania 2007 - Paradise Lost 01.jpg\n| caption             = Paradise Lost live in 2007 with former drummer Jeff Singer.\n| image_size          = 250\n| landscape           = Yes\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Halifax, West Yorkshire]], England\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n*[[Gothic metal]]<ref name=musicmight>{{cite web |author=Sharpe-Young, Garry |title=Paradise Lost biography |url=http://www.musicmight.com/artist/united+kingdom/west+yorkshire/halifax/paradise+lost |publisher=[[MusicMight]] |accessdate=2010-11-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905072521/http://www.musicmight.com/artist/united+kingdom/west+yorkshire/halifax/paradise+lost |archivedate=5 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*[[doom metal]]<ref name=allusic>{{cite web |author=Ankeny, Jason |title=Paradise Lost biography |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=paradise-lost-p13905/biography|pure_url=yes}} |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=2010-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/paradise-lost-mn0000018691|title=Paradise Lost - Biography, Albums, Streaming Links - AllMusic|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n*[[death-doom]]<ref name=\"Lost Paradise review\">{{cite web |author=Rivadavia, Eduardo |title=''Lost Paradise'' review |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=lost-paradise-r59207/review|pure_url=yes}} |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=2010-11-19}}</ref>\n*[[gothic rock]]}}\n| years_active        = 1988\u2013present\n| associated_acts= [[Vallenfyre]], [[Bloodbath]], [[The Haunted (Swedish band)|The Haunted]], [[At the Gates]], [[Cradle of Filth]], [[Blaze Bayley|Blaze]], [[Kill II This]]\n| label               = [[Century Media Records|Century Media]], [[Music for Nations]], [[Koch Records|Koch]], [[GUN Records|GUN]], [[Peaceville Records|Peaceville]], [[EMI Electrola]], [[Metal Blade Records|Metal Blade]], [[Nuclear Blast]]\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.paradiselost.co.uk/}}\n| current_members     = [[Nick Holmes (singer)|Nick Holmes]]<br/>Gregor Mackintosh<br/>Aaron Aedy<br/>Steve Edmondson<br/>Waltteri V\u00e4yrynen\n|past_members         = Matthew Archer<br/>[[Lee Morris (musician)|Lee Morris]]<br/>[[Jeff Singer]]<br/>[[Adrian Erlandsson]]\n}}\n\n'''Paradise Lost''' are a [[gothic metal]] band that formed in 1988 in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]], England, and are considered by some to be the pioneers of the [[death-doom]] genre,<ref name=allmusicInRequiem>{{cite web|last1=Bowar|first1=Chad|title=Paradise Lost - In Requiem review|url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/paradiselostin.htm|website=About.com|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> and regarded as the main influence for the later gothic metal movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anewdystopianworld.blogspot.com/2013/09/paradise-lost-lost-paradise-1990.html|title=Paradise Lost - Lost Paradise (1990)|publisher=A New Dystopian World}}</ref> Bands that have cited Paradise Lost as an influence, or have covered them, include [[My Dying Bride]],<ref name=\"pmetal\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780306818066|url-access=registration|title=Precious Metal: Decibel Presents the Stories Behind 25 Extreme Metal Masterpieces|publisher=Hachette Books|author=Albert Mudrian}}</ref> [[Anathema (band)|Anathema]],<ref name=\"pmetal\"/> [[The Gathering (band)|The Gathering]],<ref name=\"pmetal\"/> [[Amorphis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghostcultmag.com/interview-esa-holopainen-amorphis-part-2-under-the-red-cloud/|title=Gothic Tales \u2013 Esa Holopainen of Amorphis (Part II)|publisher=GhostCultMagazine}}</ref> [[Cradle of Filth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-archives.ru/rock-archive/c/cradle_of_filth/pesni_izmenivshie_moyu_zhizn.html|title=\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438, \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u044e \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c|publisher=Rock-Archives.RU|language=Russian}}</ref> [[Katatonia]],<ref name=\"Katatonia bio\">{{cite web|title=Katatonia: Short Biography|url=http://katatonia.com/biography/|publisher=Katatonia.com|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref> [[Moonspell]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rocknrolljournalist.com/2017/10/the-top-10-albums-of-fernando-ribeiro-moonspell.html|title=The Top 10 Albums Of Fernando Ribeiro (Moonspell)|publisher=Rock'n'Roll Journalist}}</ref> [[Lacuna Coil]],<ref name=\"spirit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/j55bnx/the-spirit-of-the-90s-is-alive-in-paradise-losts-new-gothic-metal-opus|title=The Spirit of the 90s Is Alive in Paradise Lost's New Gothic Metal Opus|publisher=Vice.com}}</ref> [[HIM (Finnish band)|HIM]],<ref name=\"spirit\"/> [[Nightwish]]<ref name=\"spirit\"/> and many others. As of 2005, Paradise Lost have sold over two million albums worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/artists-p-t-bandinfo-61/125-paradise-lost|title=Paradise Lost|publisher=Reflections of Darkness}}</ref>\n\nTheir line-up has remained stable for such a long-standing [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band, consisting of singer Nick Holmes, guitarists Greg Mackintosh and Aaron Aedy, and bassist Steve Edmondson. Holmes and Mackintosh are the principal [[composers]], with almost all of the band's songs credited to them. During the years, the band has only changed drummers.\n\n==History==\n===Early years and Peaceville (1988\u20131991)===\nAfter their formation in 1988, Paradise Lost released three cassette demos, ''Paradise Lost'', ''Frozen Illusion'', and ''Plains of Desolation'', before being signed to [[Peaceville Records]] in 1989. They recorded their debut album, [[Lost Paradise (album)|''Lost Paradise'']], at [[Academy Music Studio]] in December of that year. The album was released in February 1990.<ref name=allmusicBio>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p13905|pure_url=yes}} Paradise Lost Biography, at allmusic.com]</ref>\n\nIn November 1990, Paradise Lost returned to Academy Music Studio to record their second album, ''[[Gothic (Paradise Lost album)|Gothic]]'', which was released in March 1991. The band began to move away from the death/doom sound of their previous releases by adding keyboards and female vocal accompaniments.<ref name=AllmusicGothic>{{cite web|last1=Rivadavia|first1=Eduardo|title=Paradise Lost - Gothic review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/gothic-mw0000096112|website=Allmusic|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Music for Nations (1992\u20131998)===\n[[File:Paradiselost91.JPG|thumb|left|Paradise Lost performing live, 1991.]]\nParadise Lost left Peaceville and were signed to the [[Music for Nations]] label and released ''[[Shades of God]]'' in July 1992.<ref name=allmusicBio /> The band's musical approach continued to evolve with this album as evidenced by the addition of quieter passages in the song's compositions, the softening of vocalist [[Nick Holmes (singer)|Nick Holmes]]'s [[death grunt]], and Gregor Mackintosh's incorporation of [[acoustic guitar]] to his sound.<ref name=allmusicShades>{{cite web|last1=Rivadavia|first1=Eduardo|title=Paradise Lost - Shades of God review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/shades-of-god-mw0000107277|website=Allmusic|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> The album contained the song \"As I Die\", later released as a [[As I Die|single/EP]].\n\nIn summer 1993, the band recorded their fourth album, ''[[Icon (Paradise Lost album)|Icon]],'' released in September of the same year. The band continued to develop their sound away from their doom roots and more towards the dynamics and sound of \"As I Die\" from their previous album. On ''Icon'', Nick Holmes abandoned his [[death grunt]] and started using a \"[[James Hetfield]]-style bark.\"<ref name=allmusicIcon>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Christopher|title=Paradise Lost - Icon review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/icon-mw0000107875|website=Allmusic|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> It was after this album, in December 1994, that original member Matthew Archer quit and was replaced by drummer [[Lee Morris (musician)|Lee Morris]].\n\nThe band entered the studio in January 1995 to record their fifth and most successful album, ''[[Draconian Times]]'', which was released in June 1995. Mackintosh says about ''Draconian Times'', \"that it's the album by which everything else we do gets judged. Rightly so, as it\u2019s the backbone of our career and sound.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.decibelmagazine.com/2017/09/01/rank-defile-greg-mackintosh-orders-paradise-losts-records/|title=Rank and Defile: Greg Mackintosh Orders Paradise Lost\u2019s Records {{!}} Decibel Magazine|date=2017-09-01|work=Decibel Magazine|access-date=2018-02-22|language=en-US}}</ref> The album charted in the Top 20 album chart in a number of countries including the UK and Germany.\n\nFollowing the success of Draconian Times, and after four years of continuous touring, the band began to get bored with their signature sound and started to experiment with [[Depeche Mode]]-esque [[synth-pop]] and [[electronica]].<ref name=base>{{cite web|url=http://basementbar.com/DefaultN1.asp?GoTo=CurrSelN1.asp?ID=2860&Page=Archive |title=Transcending the Mundane: Metal at its Best! |publisher=Basementbar.com |date= |accessdate=2011-10-13}}</ref> This new direction shaped their next album ''[[One Second (Paradise Lost album)|One Second]],'' released in 1997, and was most epitomised by the lead single, ''Say Just Words''. The album was one of the band's most successful releases, particularly in Northern Europe, cracking the German, Swedish, and Finnish top ten charts.<ref name=GermanCharts>{{cite web|title=German charts|url=http://www.officialcharts.de/album.asp?artist=Paradise+Lost&title=One+Second&cat=a&country=de|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=SwedishCharts>{{cite web|title=Swedish charts|url=http://www.swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Paradise+Lost&titel=One+Second&cat=a|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=FinnishCharts>{{cite web|title=Finnish charts|url=http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/virallinen-lista/artistit/Paradise+Lost/One+Second|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===EMI (1999\u20132001)===\nThe band moved to [[EMI|EMI Electrola]] in Germany for its next album, ''[[Host (Paradise Lost album)|Host]]'', released in 1999, on which they continued to experiment with new sounds, appearing to shed their [[Heavy metal music|metal]] roots.<ref name=allmusicHost>{{cite web|last1=Ravelin|first1=Antti|title=Paradise Lost - Host review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/host-mw0000470698|website=Allmusic|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> While this album continued to alienate their traditional fanbase in places like the UK, it was their highest charting album in Germany, entering at number 4 on the Album Chart.\n\nOn the next album, 2001's ''[[Believe in Nothing]]'', Paradise Lost continued this synth direction but adding rock elements to the music, forcibly by EMI at the time. Due to the loss of creative control, Mackintosh said that the album \"doesn't really exist for him.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/paradise-lost-frontman-believe-in-nothing-represented-a-really-dark-time-in-my-life|title=PARADISE LOST Frontman: 'Believe In Nothing' Represented A Really Dark Time In My Life |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net|Blabbermouth]] |author=Justin Donnelly|accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===GUN Records (2002\u20132005)===\nIn May 2002, the band signed to [[GUN Records]], and on the album that followed, ''Symbol of Life'', the metallic roots of the band began to resurface.<ref name=allmusicSymbol>{{cite web|last1=Rivadavia|first1=Eduardo|title=Paradise Lost - Symbol of Life review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/symbol-of-life-mw0000225106|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> The album included guest musicians [[Devin Townsend]], [[Jamie Muhoberac]], and [[Lee Dorrian]].<ref name=allmusicSymbolCredits>{{cite web|title=Symbol of Life credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/symbol-of-life-mw0000225106/credits|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2004, [[Lee Morris (musician)|Lee Morris]] left the band and was replaced by [[Jeff Singer]].\n\nParadise Lost released their tenth, eponymous album in 2005, also on GUN Records.\n\n===Century Media (2006\u20132016)===\n[[File:Paradise Lost - Kavarna Rock Fest 2011 - 2.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Paradise Lost at [[Kavarna Rock Fest]] in Bulgaria in 2011]]\n\nThe eleventh album, ''In Requiem'', was released in the spring of 2007 on [[Century Media]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.centurymedia.com/us/single_artist.php?ID=91|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310162356/http://www.centurymedia.com/us/single_artist.php?ID=91|url-status=dead|title=Paradise Lost on Century Media Records|archivedate=10 March 2008}}</ref> it was generally well-accepted and highly rated by both critics and fans, pleased to see the band returning to their heavier, gothic metal sound similar to that of earlier albums like ''Draconian Times''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Blackie |first=Andrew |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/music/reviews/42122/paradise-lost-in-requiem/ |title=Paradise Lost: In Requiem < Music |publisher=PopMatters |date= |accessdate=2011-10-13}}</ref> The full-length was preceded by a single, \"The Enemy\" and on the single, Singer was finally listed as a permanent band member. In a recent video interview, Mackintosh and Holmes revealed that Singer had already auditioned for the band when Archer left, but they chose Morris instead because Singer \"had a pink drumkit.\"<ref>[http://194.242.113.241/rockmetal000/emission.htm Prod vid\u00e9o metal et production ind\u00e9pendante<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021091832/http://194.242.113.241/rockmetal000/emission.htm |date=21 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, Century Media released the DVD ''Over The Madness'', which documents the impact Paradise Lost has had on [[gothic metal]] and provides insight into the mindset and workings of Paradise Lost. Disc 2 includes further interviews, rehearsal footage, plus backstage and memorabilia sections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=27017_0_2_0_C |title=Double doc. DVD 'Over The Madness' for Paradise Lost |publisher=Side-line.com |date=1999-02-22 |accessdate=2011-10-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 August 2008, drummer [[Jeff Singer]] announced his departure from the band on the Paradise Lost official website. He wanted to be with his family, had an upcoming job, and the then-upcoming South American tour would interfere with that. As a result, Paradise Lost had to cancel the South American tour dates that they had planned.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102734 Paradise Lost Drummer Quits; South American Tour Cancelled] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306112225/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102734 |date=6 March 2010 }} blabbermouth.net. 2008-08-13. Retrieved on 2009-07-15.</ref> Soon after, on 28 August 2008, the Paradise Lost official website announced that the canceled South American tour has been reconfirmed<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=104369 Paradise Lost Not Cancelling South American Tour]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} blabbermouth.net. 2008-09-09. Retrieved on 2009-07-15.</ref> and that [[Mark Heron]] from [[Oceansize]] would take over on drums.\n[[File:Metalmania 2007 - Paradise Lost - Nick Holmes 02.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Nick Holmes at [[Metalmania|Metalmania 2007]] festival in [[Katowice]], Poland.]]\nAt the beginning of 2009, Paradise Lost recorded an album with producer [[Jens Bogren]] at Fascination Street Studios in \u00d6rebro, Sweden. At the time there was no full-time replacement for Jeff Singer and drums were played by Swedish drummer Peter Damin.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=114034 Paradise Lost Begins Recording New Album; Video Available]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} blabbermouth.net. 2009-02-09. Retrieved on 2009-07-15.</ref> On 16 March 2009, when recording for the album was already finished, the band recruited [[Adrian Erlandsson]] ([[At the Gates]], ex-[[Cradle of Filth]]) as a full-time drummer for the band.<ref>[http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=43152 Ex-Cradle Of Filth Drummer Adrian Erlandsson Joins Paradise Lost] metalunderground.com. 2009-03-16. Retrieved on 2009-07-15.</ref>\n\nOn 18 June 2009, Paradise Lost officially announced ''[[Faith Divides Us - Death Unites Us]]'' as the title of their album to be released on Century Media Records on 25 September 2009 in Germany, on 28 September 2009 in the rest of Europe and on 6 October 2009 in the US.<ref>[http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=45407 Paradise Lost Reveals New Album Title] metalunderground.com. 2009-06-18. Retrieved on 2009-07-15.</ref>\n\nParadise Lost headlined the J\u00e4germeister Stage at Ozzfest 2010 on 18 September 2010.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=144270 Paradise Lost To Headline 'J\u00e4germeister' Stage At U.K. Ozzfest] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817215922/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=144270 |date=17 August 2010 }} blabbermouth.net. 2010-08-10. Retrieved on 2010-09-12.</ref>\n\nIn late 2011, Paradise Lost began recording its 13th studio album ''[[Tragic Idol]]'' in The Chapel Studios in Lincolnshire. The album was released on 23 April 2012.<ref>[http://www.paradiselost.co.uk/news/2011/paradise-lost-new-album-tragic-idol.html Paradise Lost Announce New Album for 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111130032801/http://www.paradiselost.co.uk/news/2011/paradise-lost-new-album-tragic-idol.html |date=30 November 2011 }} paradiselost.co.uk. 2011-11-28. Retrieved on 2011-11-29.</ref>{{update after|2012|04|23}}. Adrian Erlandsson was unable to play a few live shows for this album so the band got Jeff Singer again to fill in.\n\nParadise Lost performed some of their songs at the ''Metal Hammer Golden Gods'' awards with [[Cristina Scabbia]] on Paradise Lost's song ''[[Say Just Words]]'' and with [[Gus G.]] of a [[Black Sabbath]] [[cover version|cover]], ''[[Into the Void (Black Sabbath song)|Into the Void]]''.\n\n[[File:Paradise Lost in Saint Petersburg 2013-8.jpg|thumb|250px|Paradise Lost performing in [[Saint Petersburg]] in 2013]]\nOn 15 August 2013, the cover and artwork were released for their [[compilation album]] of b-sides titled ''[[Tragic Illusion 25 (The Rarities)|Tragic Illusion 25]]''. In September\u2013October 2014, some of the songs from the album were released, such as a new song entitled ''Loneliness Remains'', and older songs that were remade such as ''Our Savior 2013'' from ''[[Lost Paradise (album)|Lost Paradise]]'' and the self-titled song ''Gothic 2013'' from ''[[Gothic (Paradise Lost album)|Gothic]]''. The album was released on 5 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/paradise-lost-tragic-illusion-25-the-rarities-cover-artwork-track-listing-revealed/|title=PARADISE LOST: 'Tragic Illusion 25 (The Rarities)' Cover Artwork, Track Listing Revealed|date=15 August 2013|publisher=|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October 2013, it was announced that the writing for the 14th studio album will begin after their 25th-anniversary tour and the recording to the album will start in June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/paradise-lost-to-enter-studio-in-june/ |title=Paradise Lost To Enter Studio In June |publisher=Blabbermouth.net |date=2013-10-27 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> On 29 December 2014, it was revealed that ''[[The Plague Within]]'' would be the title for upcoming album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/paradise-lost-new-album-title-revealed-2/|title=PARADISE LOST: New Album Title Revealed|date=29 December 2014|publisher=|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref> On 26 January 2015, the release date for 2 June 2015 was announced, along with the [[Record producer|producer]], Jaimie Gomez Arellano and the recording location of Orgone Studios, [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/paradise-lost-to-release-the-plague-within-album-in-june/|title=PARADISE LOST To Release 'The Plague Within' Album In June|date=26 January 2015|publisher=|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref> Speaking to Rock Sins, Nick Holmes stated that the new album would have elements of all previous Paradise Lost material including a return to the [[death/doom metal|death/doom]] of their early output, stating that \"there\u2019s some songs that could\u2019ve been written in 1989, a couple of really old school doom/death songs which are gonna surprise a couple of people when they hear it.\"<ref>[http://www.rocksins.com/2015/01/interview-nick-holmes-bloodbath-replacing-mikael-new-paradise-lost-23692/ An Interview With Nick Holmes on Bloodbath, Replacing Mikael & new Paradise Lost] Rock Sins. Retrieved 5 February 2015.</ref> ''The Plague Within'' is considered by many traditional fans to be their best and most complete album in many years, as well as being a true return to their signature sound.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/reviews/album-review-paradise-lost-the-plague-within|title=Album Review: PARADISE LOST The Plague Within - Metal Injection|date=2015-06-23|work=Metal Injection|access-date=2018-02-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Nuclear Blast (2016\u2013present)===\nOn 1 September 2017, Paradise Lost released their 15th studio album, [[Medusa (Paradise Lost album)|''Medusa.'']] The band continued their return to a much heavier, more doomier sound. Singer Nick Holmes said \"...definitely our heaviest album; the heaviest we\u2019ve done.\" Medusa was well received by fans and critics alike.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/paradise-lost-medusa-album-review/|title=Paradise Lost, 'Medusa' - Album Review|website=Loudwire|language=en|access-date=2018-02-22}}</ref>\n\n2018 marked the band's 30th anniversary and was celebrated through select dates around UK and mainland Europe, including their first gig in the hometown of Halifax, as well as a South and North American tour with [[Solstafir]] and [[The Atlas Moth]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalinjection.net/tour-dates/paradise-lost-announces-30-year-anniversary-tour-with-solstafir-the-atlas-moth|title=Paradise Lost, 30 year anniversary tour|website=Metal Injection|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> In November 2019, Decibel Books issued the band's authorized biography, <i>No Celebration: The Official Story of Paradise Lost</i>. The book was authored by American journalist David E. Gehlke. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://store.decibelmagazine.com/products/no-celebration-the-official-story-of-paradise-lost-by-david-e-gehlke|title=No Celebration: The Official Story of Paradise Lost by David E. Gehlke|website=[[Decibel Magazine]]|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Nuclear Blast announced the release of the group's 16th studio album, ''Obsidian'', on May 15. Nick Holmes described it as \"one of the most eclectic albums we have done in some time, we have miserable songs, sad songs, slow songs and faster songs. Did I mention miserable?\". First single, ''Fall from Grace'' premiered on March 20, along with a music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nuclearblast.de/en/label/music/band/news/details/6532246.4103163.paradise-lost-announce-new-album-quot-obsidian-quot.html|title=Paradise Lost, announce new album|website=Nuclear Blast|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n===Current official members===\n* [[Nick Holmes (singer)|Nick Holmes]] - [[Singing|vocals]] <small>(1988\u2013present)</small>\n* Gregor Mackintosh  - [[lead guitar]] <small>(1988\u2013present)</small>, [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]] <small>(1996\u2013present)</small>\n* Aaron Aedy - [[rhythm guitar]] <small>(1988\u2013present)</small>\n* Stephen Edmondson - [[bass guitar]] <small>(1988\u2013present)</small>\n* Waltteri V\u00e4yrynen - drums <small>(2015\u2013present)</small>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" caption=\"Paradise Lost, Line-Up at Rockharz Open Air 2018\">\nFile:Paradise Lost Rockharz 2018 15.jpg|Singer Nick Holmes\nFile:Paradise Lost Rockharz 2018 14.jpg|Lead guitarist Gregor Mackintosh\nFile:Paradise Lost Rockharz 2018 20.jpg|Rhythm guitarist Aaron Aedy\nFile:Paradise Lost Rockharz 2018 06.jpg|Bassist Stephen Edmondson\nFile:Paradise Lost Rockharz 2018 04.jpg|Drummer Waltteri V\u00e4yrynen\n</gallery>\n\n===Former members===\n====Drummers====\n* Matthew Archer \u2013 <small>(1988\u20131994)</small>\n* [[Lee Morris (musician)|Lee Morris]] \u2013 <small>(1994\u20132004)</small>\n* [[Jeff Singer]] \u2013 <small>(2004\u20132008)</small>\n* Mark Heron \u2013 [[session musician]] <small>(2008-2009)</small>\n* Peter Damin \u2013 <small> (2009)</small>\n* [[Adrian Erlandsson]] \u2013 <small>(2009-2015)</small>\n\n====Multi-Instrumentalist====\n* Milton Evans - session lead guitar <small>(1999)</small>, keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2011)</small>\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:1000 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:140 bottom:120 top:0 right:0\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1988 till:{{#time:m/d/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:horizontal positio