n[[Category:Nuclear Blast artists]]\n[[Category:Music for Nations artists]]\n", "name_user": "EOD0905", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDiscography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paradise_Lost_(band)"}
{"title_page": "Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = Doctor Wooreddy cover.jpg\n| caption = \n| author        = Mudrooroo Nyoongah (Colin Johnson)\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = Terry Yumbulul\n| country       = [[Australia]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| series        = \n| subject       = \n| genre         = [[Historical novel]]\n| publisher     = University of Queensland Press\n| pub_date      = 1983\n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type    = [[Paperback]]\n| pages         = 207\n| isbn          = 978-0-947062-02-6\n| dewey= 823/.54 22\n| congress= PR9619.3.N32 D63 1983\n| oclc= 26559359\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n'''''Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World''''' is an [[historical novel]] by [[Mudrooroo]] Nyoongah, first published in 1983.<ref>{{cite conference\n  | first = Eva\n  | last = Rask Knudsen\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Mission Completed? On Mudrooroo's Contribution to the Politics of \n  | booktitle = Missions of Interdependence: A Literary Directory\n  | pages = 322\n  | publisher = [[Rodopi Publishers]] \n  | year = 2002\n  | location = \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=mZu673jjxAcC\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = 2009-01-22 }}\n</ref> A tragedy, it explores how [[Aboriginal Tasmanians|Aboriginal Tasmanians']] dealt with British colonisation during the nineteenth century. It has several characters based on real-life historical figures, including [[Truganini]], [[George Augustus Robinson]], and [[George Arthur|Governor George Arthur]]. \n\nThe story is told almost exclusively from the perspective of its protagonist, Wooreddy (based on the real-life figure of Worraddy, a [[Nuenonne language|Nueonne]] man from [[Bruny Island|North Bruny Island]]).<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Concise Companion to Aboriginal History|last=Prentis, Malcolm D.|date=2012|publisher=Rosenberg|isbn=|location=|pages=228|oclc=940741557}}</ref> A few moments are told from the point of view of 'Mr Robinson'.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tompkins|first=Joanne|date=1990|title=\"It all depends on what story you hear\": Historiographic Metafiction and Colin Johnson's <i>Dr. Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World</i> and Witi Ihimaera's <i>The Matriarch</i>|journal=MFS Modern Fiction Studies|volume=36|issue=4|pages=483\u2013498 (492)|doi=10.1353/mfs.0.0636|issn=1080-658X}}</ref> The novel focuses on the relationships between Wooreddy, his companions, and Robinson - who was sent by [[Great Britain]] to [[Tasmania]] to act as a '[[conciliation|conciliator]]' between them and the British settlers. It also deals with Robinson's relationship with \"Trugernanna\" (based on the real-life [[Trugernanner]], widely considered to be the last full-blooded Aboriginal Tasmanian). Justin MacGregor suggests that Robinson's presence \"allows for a reversal of the colonial contact novel: ... here it is the Aboriginals who are depicted as human and spiritual, and the invaders, the white ghosts or ''num'', who are treated as curiosities. ...  there is little doubt that [the author] sees [Robinson] unsympathetically as a self-aggrandized co-conspirator in the colonial process who is more ridiculous than sympathetic\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=MacGregor|first=Justin|date=December 1992|title=A Margin's History: Mudrooroo Narogin's \"Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduringthe Ending of the World|journal=Antipodes|volume=6|issue=2|pages=113-118 (114, 118)|jstor=41958358}}</ref> \n\nThroughout the narrative the violence of colonisation is documented and explored: \"a clear parallel is established between the rape of the Tasmanian Aboriginal women and the metaphorical rape of their land, sacred sites and heritage.\"<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Shoemaker\n  | first = Adam\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Black Words White Page: Aboriginal literature 1929-1988\n  | publisher = [[University of Queensland Press|UQP]]\n  | location = Brisbane\n  | year = 1989\n  | pages = 161\n  | isbn = 978-0-7022-2149-1 }}</ref> David Kerr argues that the four characters \u2013 Wooreddy, Trugernanna, Ummarrah and Wayler \u2013 each represent a major stance taken by Aboriginal Tasmanians in order to deal with colonial rule.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mudrooroo a likely story : identity and belonging in postcolonial Australia|last=Clark, Maureen.|date=2007|publisher=P.I.E. Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-356-5|location=|pages=140|oclc=496778800}}</ref> Despite their struggles, and the deaths of many key characters, some have seen the ending as hinting \"at the possibility of successful cross-cultural communication\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Characters==\n* Wooreddy (''Woorrady'') - The main character of the novel, who befriends Mr. Robinson. As a boy, he finds an omen from the sea that he believes is predicting the end of the world. \n* Mr. Robinson (''[[George Augustus Robinson]]'') - Sent to [[Bruny Island]] to 'protect' the Aborigines, later sent on an expedition to contact the natives on [[Tasmania]] and help bring them under British control. Known by the natives as \"Meeter Ro-bin-un,\" \"Fader,\" and \"Ballawine.\"\n* Trugernanna (''[[Trugernanner]]'') - The second wife of Wooreddy who he knows from the start of puberty. \n* Mangana - Trugernanna's father, who helps educate Wooreddy. The last surviving man on Bruny Island, he recognizes the coming doom of his people.\n* Wayler - A female leader of a band of Aboriginal [[guerrilla warfare|guerrillas]].\n* Ummarrah - An Aboriginal Tasmanian who accompanies part of Robinson's expedition through his homeland. A prideful warrior, he was previously captured by the British and sneaks off the journey to return to his homeland, where he joins Wayler's raiding party.\n*[[George Arthur|Governor George Arthur]] - Governor of [[Van Diemen's Land]] (now [[Tasmania]], [[Australia]]), a supporter of Robinson who aids his expedition.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Mudrooroo Nyoongah, ''Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World'' {{ISBN|978-0-947062-02-6}}\n\n[[Category:1983 Australian novels]]\n[[Category:Books about Indigenous Australians]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Australian historical novels]]\n[[Category:University of Queensland Press books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = Doctor Wooreddy cover.jpg\n| caption = \n| author        = Mudrooroo Nyoongah (Colin Johnson)\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = Terry Yumbulul\n| country       = [[Australia]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| series        = \n| subject       = \n| genre         = [[Historical novel]]\n| publisher     = University of Queensland Press\n| pub_date      = 1983\n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type    = [[Paperback]]\n| pages         = 207\n| isbn          = 978-0-947062-02-6\n| dewey= 823/.54 22\n| congress= PR9619.3.N32 D63 1983\n| oclc= 26559359\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n'''''Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World''''' is an [[historical novel]] by [[Mudrooroo]] Nyoongah, first published in 1983.<ref>{{cite conference\n  | first = Eva\n  | last = Rask Knudsen\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Mission Completed? On Mudrooroo's Contribution to the Politics of \n  | booktitle = Missions of Interdependence: A Literary Directory\n  | pages = 322\n  | publisher = [[Rodopi Publishers]] \n  | year = 2002\n  | location = \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=mZu673jjxAcC\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | accessdate = 2009-01-22 }}\n</ref> A tragedy, it explores how [[Aboriginal Tasmanians|Aboriginal Tasmanians']] dealt with British colonisation during the nineteenth century. It has several characters based on real-life historical figures, including [[Truganini]], [[George Augustus Robinson]], and [[George Arthur|Governor George Arthur]]. \n\nThe story is told almost exclusively from the perspective of its protagonist, Wooreddy (based on the real-life figure of Worraddy, a [[Nuenonne language|Nueonne]] man from [[Bruny Island|North Bruny Island]]).<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Concise Companion to Aboriginal History|last=Prentis, Malcolm D.|date=2012|publisher=Rosenberg|isbn=|location=|pages=228|oclc=940741557}}</ref> A few moments are told from the point of view of 'Mr Robinson'.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tompkins|first=Joanne|date=1990|title=\"It all depends on what story you hear\": Historiographic Metafiction and Colin Johnson's <i>Dr. Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World</i> and Witi Ihimaera's <i>The Matriarch</i>|journal=MFS Modern Fiction Studies|volume=36|issue=4|pages=483\u2013498 (492)|doi=10.1353/mfs.0.0636|issn=1080-658X}}</ref> The novel focuses on the relationships between Wooreddy, his companions, and Robinson - who was sent by [[Great Britain]] to [[Tasmania]] to act as a '[[conciliation|conciliator]]' between them and the British settlers. It also deals with Robinson's relationship with \"Trugernanna\" (based on the real-life [[Trugernanner]], widely considered to be the last full-blooded Aboriginal Tasmanian). Justin MacGregor suggests that Robinson's presence \"allows for a reversal of the colonial contact novel: ... here it is the Aboriginals who are depicted as human and spiritual, and the invaders, the white ghosts or ''num'', who are treated as curiosities. ...  there is little doubt that [the author] sees [Robinson] unsympathetically as a self-aggrandized co-conspirator in the colonial process who is more ridiculous than sympathetic\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=MacGregor|first=Justin|date=December 1992|title=A Margin's History: Mudrooroo Narogin's \"Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduringthe Ending of the World|journal=Antipodes|volume=6|issue=2|pages=113-118 (114, 118)|jstor=41958358}}</ref> \n\nThroughout the narrative the violence of colonisation is documented and explored: \"a clear parallel is established between the rape of the Tasmanian Aboriginal women and the metaphorical rape of their land, sacred sites and heritage.\"<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Shoemaker\n  | first = Adam\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Black Words White Page: Aboriginal literature 1929-1988\n  | publisher = [[University of Queensland Press|UQP]]\n  | location = Brisbane\n  | year = 1989\n  | pages = 161\n  | isbn = 978-0-7022-2149-1 }}</ref> David Kerr argues that the four charaters Wooreddy, Trugernanna, Ummarrah and Wayler each represent a major stance taken by Aboriginal Tasmanians in order to deal with colonial rule.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mudrooroo a likely story : identity and belonging in postcolonial Australia|last=Clark, Maureen.|date=2007|publisher=P.I.E. Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-356-5|location=|pages=140|oclc=496778800}}</ref> Despite their struggles, and the deaths of many key characters, some have seen the ending as hinting \"at the possibility of successful cross-cultural communication\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Characters==\n* Wooreddy (''Woorrady'') - The main character of the novel, who befriends Mr. Robinson. As a boy, he finds an omen from the sea that he believes is predicting the end of the world. \n* Mr. Robinson (''[[George Augustus Robinson]]'') - Sent to [[Bruny Island]] to 'protect' the Aborigines, later sent on an expedition to contact the natives on [[Tasmania]] and help bring them under British control. Known by the natives as \"Meeter Ro-bin-un,\" \"Fader,\" and \"Ballawine.\"\n* Trugernanna (''[[Trugernanner]]'') - The second wife of Wooreddy who he knows from the start of puberty. \n* Mangana - Trugernanna's father, who helps educate Wooreddy. The last surviving man on Bruny Island, he recognizes the coming doom of his people.\n* Wayler - A female leader of a band of Aboriginal [[guerrilla warfare|guerrillas]].\n* Ummarrah - An Aboriginal Tasmanian who accompanies part of Robinson's expedition through his homeland. A prideful warrior, he was previously captured by the British and sneaks off the journey to return to his homeland, where he joins Wayler's raiding party.\n*[[George Arthur|Governor George Arthur]] - Governor of [[Van Diemen's Land]] (now [[Tasmania]], [[Australia]]), a supporter of Robinson who aids his expedition.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Mudrooroo Nyoongah, ''Doctor Wooreddy's Prescription for Enduring the Ending of the World'' {{ISBN|978-0-947062-02-6}}\n\n[[Category:1983 Australian novels]]\n[[Category:Books about Indigenous Australians]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Australian historical novels]]\n[[Category:University of Queensland Press books]]\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling, c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_Wooreddy%27s_Prescription_for_Enduring_the_Ending_of_the_World"}
{"title_page": "Kakkakuyil", "text_new": "{{short description|2001 film by Priyadarshan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kakkakuyil\n| image          = Kakkakuyil poster.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = DVD Cover\n| director       = [[Priyadarshan]]\n| producer       = [[Lissy (actress)|Lissy]]\n| story          = Murali Nagavally\n| screenplay     = Priyadarshan\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Mohanlal]]<br />[[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]<br />[[Nedumudi Venu]]<br />[[Arzoo Govitrikar]]<br />[[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]]<br />[[Sucheta Khanna]]<br />[[Jagathy Sreekumar]]<br />[[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]]\n| music          = Deepan Chatterji<br />[[S. P. Venkatesh]] {{small|(Score)}}\n| cinematography = [[S. Kumar (cinematographer)|S. Kumar]]\n| editing        = N. Gopalakrishnan\n| studio         = Kalyani Film Society\n| distributor    = [[Swargachitra Appachan|Swargachitra]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2001|4|14}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Malayalam]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Kakkakuyil''''' ({{Literal translation|Crow-[[Koel]]}}) is a 2001 Indian [[Malayalam]]-language [[Heist film|heist]] [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Priyadarshan]] and produced by [[Lissy (actress)|Lissy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surfindia.com/celebrities/bollywood/priyadarshan.html|title=Priyadarshan|publisher=surfindia.com|accessdate=2009-07-18}}</ref> It stars [[Mohanlal]] and [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]], with [[Arzoo Govitrikar]], [[Nedumudi Venu]], [[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]], [[Sucheta Khanna]], [[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]], and [[Jagathy Sreekumar]] in pivotal roles. [[Suniel Shetty]] and [[Ramya Krishnan]] makes [[cameo appearance]]s. The film features songs composed by Deepan Chatterji and background score by [[S. P. Venkatesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artkerala.com/node/5698|title=Kakkakuyil&nbsp;\u2014 Malayalam Priyadarshan. Mohanlal comedy Movie|work=artkerala.com|accessdate=2009-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704014414/http://artkerala.com/node/5698|archive-date=4 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKakkakuyil was released on 14 April 2001. It was remade in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] as ''Tappu Chesi Pappu Koodu'' (2002) and in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as ''[[London (2005 Indian film)|London]]'' (2005). The core plot of the movie is based on the 1988 English movie ''[[A Fish Called Wanda]]'' and the sub plot of the blind couple is adapted from the Marathi play '' Ghar Ghar'' which also went on to be adapted in the 2006 Hindi film ''[[Golmaal: Fun Unlimited]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nSivaraman ([[Mohanlal]]), an unemployed man, comes to [[Mumbai]] to find a job. Unfortunately, he loses all his certificates but happens to find Govindan Kutty ([[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]), an old buddy from his native place, who is also jobless and wandering in Mumbai. They try to get [[Travel visa|visa]] from a travel agency but finds no way to gather such a massive amount. Govindan Kutty persuades Sivaraman to participate in a bank robbery planned by Thomas ([[Cochin Haneefa]]) and his gang, including his stammering brother Tyootty ([[Jagadish]]) and lover Alina ([[Sucheta Khanna]]).\n\nThey join the gang but the plan puts them in more trouble as the robbery ends in vain when they hit Pothuval ([[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]]). Alina secretly informs the police about the robbery and tells that the entire plan was carried out by Thomas. Thomas, before getting arrested, hides the money, and the place is kept secret except to his lawyer, Nambeeshan ([[Jagathy Sreekumar]]). Alina pretends to be in love with Nambeeshan to find the place where the money is hidden.\n\nMeanwhile, to find a safe cover, Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty plan to impersonate Kunjunni, the grandson of a rich but blind elderly couple, Thampuran ([[Nedumudi Venu]]) and his wife Sethu ([[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]]). They haven't seen their grandchild since his childhood. Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty end up disguising with the body of Govindan Kutty and the voice of Sivaraman to make up for Kunjunni in front of the blind couple.\n\nPothuval, who knows Govindan Kutty before and who served as a former servant to the blind couple, makes several attempts to make the old man learn the truth, but all of them fail knowingly or unknowingly much to the luck of Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty. While successfully carrying on, they are interrupted by Radhika Menon ([[Arzoo Govitrikar]]) who disguises herself as the lover of Kunjunni. She calls on all the relatives of the couple by mocking them. The relatives arrive in the absence of Sivaraman. Finding no-way out, Govindan Kutty pretends to have fainted unconscious and he gets admitted to the hospital. Sivaraman comes to his rescue and says that he is Dr. Gopalakrishnan, a friend of Kunjunni from the [[United States]]. \n\nAfter many successful and comical escapades during their drama, Govindan Kutty tries to steal the [[Lord Krishna]] statue, for which he places a [[Tepoy]] in the staircase to injure the old woman which keeps all others out of the house for sometime. Sivaraman engages in a fight with Govindan Kutty when he tries to leave with the statue he had stolen. The old man accuses his relatives for the accident and asks all his relatives to leave immediately. While he was reprimanding the relatives, the duo learn that the elderly couple had become blind in a car accident decades ago, in which their son and daughter-in-law (Kunjunni's parents) had died. Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty get desperate as the date for the visa payment was nearing. Radhika gives them the money for the visa and asks them to leave the house. Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty accept the money and leave the house.\n\nUpon leaving, they come to know that the visa agency was a fake one. Having lost all their resources, Govindan Kutty plans to start some new business with the money they have. Sivaraman disagrees to take the money and asks Govindan Kutty not to take the money which they have got for cheating on the innocent old couple. Govindankutty leaves Sivaraman in anger taking the money with him. Meanwhile, a sorrowful Pothuval informs Thampuran about Kunjunni's death. Later, Radhika also reveals to the old man that she is Kunjunni's actual lover and her real name is 'Revathy'. She also tells him that Kunjunni tragically died in [[America]] in a construction-site accident and she had come to inform this. But, after seeing the drama that was taking place which kept the old couple happy, cheerful, and hopeful, she also joined the duo. Sivaraman hears the truth and returns to the old man and confesses all his mistakes. The old man asks him to continue the drama in front of his wife Sethu, who loves her grandson above all and will die on the spot if she comes to know about the tragic truth. Sethu comes and calls Kunjunni, but she gets no replies but finally gets hold of Govindan Kutty's arms who has returned in remorse. The emotional old man hugs both Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty. And, while going back, Radhika promises to the old man that she will return again. Thampuran, Sivaraman, and Govindan Kutty have a funny moment together.\n\nIn the closing scene it is shown that Thomas and Tyootty have started a new humbug. Nambeeshan has gone back to his native place and has started farming and his ex-wife ([[Sukumari]]) marries a younger man. Pothuval starts an anti-alcohol society, and the future plans of Alina remain unknown.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Mohanlal]] as Sivaraman / Kunjunni\n* [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] as Govindan Kutty / Dr. Gopalakrishnan\n* [[Arzoo Govitrikar]] as Radhika Menon / Revathy, Kunjunni's lover \n* [[Suniel Shetty]] as the real Kunjunni ([[Cameo appearance]])\n* [[Nedumudi Venu]] as 'Thampuran', Kunjunni's blind grandfather\n* [[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]] as Sethulakshmi Bai 'Thampuratti', Kunjunni's blind grandmother\n* [[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]] as Pothuval\n* [[Jagathy Sreekumar]] as Advocate Nambeeshan\n* [[Sukumari]] as Savitri, Nambeeshan's wife\n* [[Sucheta Khanna]] as Elena (voice dubbed by [[Sreeja Ravi]])\n* [[Cochin Haneefa]] as Thomas\n* [[Jagadish]] as Tyootty, Thomas' stammering brother\n* [[Shalu Menon]] as Shalini, Devooty's daughter\n* [[Augustine (actor)|Augustine]] as Rama Varma, real Kunjunni's uncle\n* Poornima Anand as Thampuran and Thampuratti's daughter\n* [[Suchitra Murali]] as Madhavan's daughter\n* Manka Mahesh as Devooty, Thampuran and Thampuratti's daughter\n* [[T. P. Madhavan]] as Dy. S.P Madhava Varma, Thampuran's younger brother\n* James Stalin as Ramettan, Devooty's husband\n* Ajayan Adoor as Doctor Rajan \n* [[Vallathol Unnikrishnan]] as Thampuran's son-in-law\n* [[Shweta Menon]] as Dancer in the song ''Alare Govinda''\n* [[Ramya Krishnan]] as Dancer in the song ''Megharagam Nerukil''\n{{colend}}\n\n== Production ==\n[[Jyothika]] was selected as lead actress but was later replaced due to further commitments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemalayalam.net/movie/Kakkakuyil/3074|title=Kakkakuyil|publisher=cinemalayalam.net|accessdate=2009-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Kakkakuyil\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = Deepan Chatterjee\n| cover        = \n| released     = 1 January 2001\n| recorded     = \n| genre        = [[Popular music]]\n| length       = 39.31\n| label        = East Coast Audio Entertainments\n| producer     = [[Lissy (actress)|Lissy]]\n}}\n\nThe songs in the film were composed by Deepan Chatterji with lyrics by [[Gireesh Puthenchery]]. [[S. P. Venkatesh]] composed the background music. The soundtrack album was released on 1 January 2001 by East Coast Audio Entertainments.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kakkakuyil (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) by Deepan Chaterjee |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/kakkakuyil-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/883723931 |publisher=[[iTunes]] |accessdate=10 September 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline     = Kakkakuyil (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n\n| title1       = Aararum Kandillenno\n| extra1       = [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[Sujatha Mohan]]\n| length1      = 4:12\n\n| title2       = Padam Vanamali\n| extra2       = [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[K. S. Chithra]], Kalyani Menon\n| length2      = 5:21\n\n| title3       = Ponnumani Kannanunni\n| note3        = Female Vocals\n| extra3       = [[Sujatha Mohan]], Kalyani Menon\n| length3      = 5:57\n\n| title4       = Megharagam Nerukil\n| note4        = Male Vocals\n| extra4       = [[M. G. Sreekumar]]\n| length4      = 4:41\n\n| title5       = Unnikanna Vayo\n| extra5       = Kalyani Menon\n| length5      = 0:43\n\n| title6       = Kakkakuyile Karuke Kuruke\n| extra6       = [[M. G. Sreekumar]]\n| length6      = 4:33\n\n| title7       = Megharagam Nerukil\n| note7        = Female Vocals\n| extra7       = [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| length7      = 4:41\n\n| title8       = Ponnumani Kannanunni\n| note8        = Male Vocals\n| extra8       = [[M. G. Sreekumar]]\n| length8      = 5:56\n\n| title9       = Alare Govinda\n| extra9       = [[M. G. Sreekumar]], Sangeetha Sajith, [[Nikhil Mathew|Nikhil]]\n| length9      = 5:25\n}}\n\n==Box office==\nThe film was a super-hit at the box office.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0277774}}\n\n{{Priyadarshan}}\n\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2000s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:Malayalam films remade in other languages]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2001 film by Priyadarshan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kakkakuyil\n| image          = Kakkakuyil poster.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = DVD Cover\n| director       = [[Priyadarshan]]\n| producer       = [[Lissy (actress)|Lissy]]\n| story          = Murali Nagavally\n| screenplay     = Priyadarshan\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Mohanlal]]<br />[[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]<br />[[Nedumudi Venu]]<br />[[Arzoo Govitrikar]]<br />[[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]]<br />[[Sucheta Khanna]]<br />[[Jagathy Sreekumar]]<br />[[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]]\n| music          = Deepan Chatterji<br />[[S. P. Venkatesh]] {{small|(Score)}}\n| cinematography = [[S. Kumar (cinematographer)|S. Kumar]]\n| editing        = N. Gopalakrishnan\n| studio         = Kalyani Film Society\n| distributor    = [[Swargachitra Appachan|Swargachitra]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2001|4|14}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Malayalam]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Kakkakuyil''''' ({{Literal translation|Crow-[[Koel]]}}) is a 2001 Indian [[Malayalam]]-language [[Heist film|heist]] [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Priyadarshan]] and produced by [[Lissy (actress)|Lissy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surfindia.com/celebrities/bollywood/priyadarshan.html|title=Priyadarshan|publisher=surfindia.com|accessdate=2009-07-18}}</ref> It stars [[Mohanlal]] and [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]], with [[Arzoo Govitrikar]], [[Nedumudi Venu]], [[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]], [[Sucheta Khanna]], [[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]], and [[Jagathy Sreekumar]] in pivotal roles. [[Suniel Shetty]] and [[Ramya Krishnan]] makes [[cameo appearance]]s. The film features songs composed by Deepan Chatterji and background score by [[S. P. Venkatesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artkerala.com/node/5698|title=Kakkakuyil&nbsp;\u2014 Malayalam Priyadarshan. Mohanlal comedy Movie|work=artkerala.com|accessdate=2009-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704014414/http://artkerala.com/node/5698|archive-date=4 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKakkakuyil was released on 14 April 2001. It was remade in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] as ''Tappu Chesi Pappu Koodu'' (2002) and in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as ''[[London (2005 Indian film)|London]]'' (2005). The core plot of the movie is based on the 1988 English movie ''[[A Fish Called Wanda]]'' and the sub plot of the blind couple is adapted from the Marathi play '' Ghar Ghar'' which also went on to be adapted in the 2006 Hindi film ''[[Golmaal: Fun Unlimited]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nSivaraman ([[Mohanlal]]), an unemployed man, comes to [[Mumbai]] to find a job. Unfortunately, he loses all his certificates but happens to find Govindan Kutty ([[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]), an old buddy from his native place, who is also jobless and wandering in Mumbai. They try to get [[Travel visa|visa]] from a travel agency but finds no way to gather such a massive amount.  Govindan Kutty persuades Sivaraman to participate in a bank robbery planned by Thomas ([[Cochin Haneefa]]) and his gang, including his stammering brother Tyootty ([[Jagadish]]) and lover Alina ([[Sucheta Khanna]]).\n\nThey join the gang but the plan puts them in more trouble as the robbery ends in vain when they hit Pothuval ([[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]]). Alina secretly informs the police about the robbery and tells that the entire plan was carried out by Thomas. Thomas, before getting arrested, hides the money, and the place is kept secret except to his lawyer, Nambeeshan ([[Jagathy Sreekumar]]). Alina pretends to be in love with Nambeeshan to find the place where the money is hidden.\n\nMeanwhile, to find a safe cover, Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty plan to impersonate Kunjunni, the grandson of a rich but blind elderly couple, Thampuran ([[Nedumudi Venu]]) and his wife Sethu ([[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]]). They haven't seen their grandchild since his childhood. Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty end up disguising with the body of Govindan Kutty and the voice of Sivaraman to make up for Kunjunni in front of the blind couple.\n\nPothuval, who knows Govindan Kutty before and who served as a former servant to the blind couple, makes several attempts to make the old man learn the truth, but all of them fail knowingly or unknowingly much to the luck of Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty. While successfully carrying on, they are interrupted by Radhika Menon ([[Arzoo Govitrikar]]) who disguises herself as the lover of Kunjunni. She calls on all the relatives of the couple by mocking them. The relatives arrive in the absence of Sivaraman. Finding no-way out, Govindan Kutty pretends to have fainted unconscious and he gets admitted to the hospital. Sivaraman comes to his rescue and says that he is Dr. Gopalakrishnan, a friend of Kunjunni from the [[United States]]. \n\nAfter many successful and comical escapades during their drama, Govindan Kutty tries to steal the [[Lord Krishna]] statue, for which he places a [[Tepoy]] in the staircase to injure the old woman which keeps all others out of the house for sometime. Sivaraman engages in a fight with Govindan Kutty when he tries to leave with the statue he had stolen. The old man accuses his relatives for the accident and asks all his relatives to leave immediately. While he was reprimanding the relatives, the duo learn that the elderly couple had become blind in a car accident decades ago, in which their son and daughter-in law (Kunjunni's parents) had died. Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty get desperate as the date for the visa payment was nearing. Radhika gives them the money for the visa and asks them to leave the house. Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty accept the money and leave the house.\n\nUpon leaving, they come to know that the visa agency was a fake one. Having lost all their resources, Govindan Kutty plans to start some new business with the money they have. Sivaraman disagrees to take the money and asks Govindan Kutty not to take the money which they have got for cheating on the innocent old couple. Govindankutty leaves Sivaraman in anger taking the money with him. Meanwhile, a sorrowful Pothuval informs Thampuran about Kunjunni's death. Later, Radhika also reveals to the old man that she is Kunjunni's actual lover and her real name is 'Revathy'. She also tells him that Kunjunni tragically died in [[America]] in a construction-site accident and she had come to inform this. But, after seeing the drama that was taking place which kept the old couple happy, cheerful, and hopeful, she also joined the duo. Sivaraman hears the truth and returns to the old man and confesses all his mistakes. The old man asks him to continue the drama in front of his wife Sethu, who loves her grandson above all and will die on the spot if she comes to know about the tragic truth. Sethu comes and calls Kunjunni, but she gets no replies but finally gets hold of Govindan Kutty's arms who has returned in remorse. The emotional old man hugs both Sivaraman and Govindan Kutty. And, while going back, Radhika promises to the old man that she will return again. Thampuran, Sivaraman, and Govindan Kutty have a funny moment together.\n\nIn the closing scene it is shown that Thomas and Tyootty have started a new humbug. Nambeeshan has gone back to his native place and has started farming and his ex-wife ([[Sukumari]]) gets married to a younger man. Pothuval starts an anti-alcohol society, and the future plans of Alina are still unknown.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Mohanlal]] as Sivaraman / Kunjunni\n* [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] as Govindan Kutty / Dr. Gopalakrishnan\n* [[Arzoo Govitrikar]] as Radhika Menon / Revathy, Kunjunni's lover \n* [[Suniel Shetty]] as the real Kunjunni ([[Cameo Appearance]])\n* [[Nedumudi Venu]] as 'Thampuran', Kunjunni's blind grandfather\n* [[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]] as Sethulakshmi Bai 'Thampuratti', Kunjunni's blind grandmother\n* [[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]] as Pothuval\n* [[Jagathy Sreekumar]] as Advocate Nambeeshan\n* [[Sukumari]] as Savitri, Nambeeshan's wife\n* [[Sucheta Khanna]] as Elena   (voice dubbed by [[Sreeja Ravi]])\n* [[Cochin Haneefa]] as Thomas\n* [[Jagadish]] as Tyootty, Thomas's stammering brother\n* [[Shalu Menon]] as Shalini, Devooty's daughter\n* [[Augustine (actor)|Augustine]] as Rama Varma, real Kunjunni's uncle\n* Poornima Anand as Thampuran and Thampuratti's daughter\n* [[Suchitra Murali]] as Madhavan's daughter\n* Manka Mahesh as Devooty, Thampuran and Thampuratti's daughter\n* [[T. P. Madhavan]] as Dy. S.P Madhava Varma, Thampuran's younger brother\n* James Stalin as Ramettan, Devooty's husband\n* Ajayan Adoor as Doctor Rajan \n* [[Vallathol Unnikrishnan]] as Thampuran's son-in-law\n* [[Shweta Menon]] as Dancer in the song ''Alare Govinda'' ([[Guest Appearance]])\n* [[Ramya Krishnan]] as Dancer in the song ''Megharagam Nerukil'' ([[Guest appearance]])\n{{colend}}\n\n== Production ==\n[[Jyothika]] was selected as lead actress but was later replaced due to further commitments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemalayalam.net/movie/Kakkakuyil/3074|title=Kakkakuyil|publisher=cinemalayalam.net|accessdate=2009-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Kakkakuyil\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = Deepan Chatterjee\n| cover        = \n| released     = 1 January 2001\n| recorded     = \n| genre        = [[Popular music]]\n| length       = 39.31\n| label        = East Coast Audio Entertainments\n| producer     = [[Lissy (actress)|Lissy]]\n}}\n\nThe songs in the film were composed by Deepan Chatterji with lyrics by [[Gireesh Puthenchery]]. [[S. P. Venkatesh]] composed the background music. The soundtrack album was released on 1 January 2001 by East Coast Audio Entertainments.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kakkakuyil (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) by Deepan Chaterjee |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/kakkakuyil-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/883723931 |publisher=[[iTunes]] |accessdate=10 September 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline     = Kakkakuyil (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n\n| title1       = Aararum Kandillenno\n| extra1       = [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[Sujatha Mohan]]\n| length1      = 4:12\n\n| title2       = 